5 6 CHAP. 6. erant omnino, there were in all, i.e. only. —itinera . . . itineribus: observe the form of this relative sentence, common in Caesar, which gives the antecedent noun in both clauses, It is usually omitted in one or the other; in English, almost always in the relative clause; in Latin, quite as often in the other; §307 (200); B. 251. 3; G. 615; H. 399. 5 (445. 8); H-B. 284. 4.
